"Lu J., Cai M.","Seasonality of polar surface warming amplification in climate simulations",2009,"Geophysical Research Letters","36","16", L16704,"","",,,10.1029/2009GL040133,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-71949125607&partnerID=40&md5=ed6a80910bb98bc747a6dbd8ae294899","Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Institute, Florida State University, 018 Keen Building, Tallahassee, FL 32306, United States; Department of Meteorology, Florida State University, 418 Love Building, Tallahassee, FL 32306, United States","Lu, J., Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Institute, Florida State University, 018 Keen Building, Tallahassee, FL 32306, United States; Cai, M., Department of Meteorology, Florida State University, 418 Love Building, Tallahassee, FL 32306, United States","The IPCC AR4 global warming climate simulations reveal a pronounced seasonality of polar warming amplification with maximum warming amplification in winter and minimum in summer. In this paper, we study me relative importance of surface albedo feedback (SAF), changes in cloud radiative forcing (CRF), changes in surface sensible and latent heat fluxes, changes in heat storage, and changes in me clear-sky downward infrared radiation in causing the strong seasonality of polar warming amplification by calculating partial temperature changes due to each of these processes using me surface energy budget equation. The main thermodynamic factor for a small polar warming amplification in summer is mat me positive SAF is largely cancelled out by the negative surface CRF feedback in summer. The positive SAF is relatively much weaker in winter compared to its amplitude in summer, therefore does not contribute to the pronounced polar warming amplification in winter. The seasonal cycle, of polar surface warming amplification, in terms of both spatial patterns and temporal amplitude, closely follows the seasonal cycle of the warming due to changes in clear-sky downward longwave radiation alone,' indicating the importance of the atmospheric processes, such as water vapor feedback and dynamical feedbacks associated wim the enhancement of poleward moist static energy transport, in causing the pronounced seasonality of polar warming amplification. Copyright 2009 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric movements; Feedback; Global warming; Heat storage; Infrared radiation; Surface chemistry; Surface tension; Water vapor; Atmospheric process; Climate simulation; Cloud radiative forcing; Long-wave radiation; Moist static energy; Polar surfaces; Relative importance; Seasonal cycle; Seasonality; Sensible and latent heat fluxes; Spatial patterns; Surface albedo; Surface energy budget; Temperature changes; Thermodynamic factors; Water vapor feedbacks; Amplification; albedo; clear sky; climate feedback; climate modeling; cloud radiative forcing; energy budget; global warming; heat flux; Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change; seasonality; surface energy; water vapor",,,,,,"Bitz, C.M., Fu, Q., Arctic warming aloft is data set dependent (2008) Nature, 455, pp. E3-E4. , doi:10.1038/nature07258; Cai, M., Dynamical amplification of polar warming (2005) Geophys. Res. Lett, 32, pp. L22710. , doi:10.1029/2005GL024481; Cai, M., Lu, J.-H., A new framework for isolating individual feedback processes in coupled general circulation climate models. Part II: Method demonstrations and comparisons (2008) Clim. Dyn., 32, pp. 887-900. , doi: 10.1007/s00382-008-0424-4; Cess, R.D., Potter, G.L., A methodology for understanding and intercomparing atmospheric climate feedback processes in general circulation models (1988) J. Geophys. Res., 93, pp. 8305-8314. , doi:10.1029/ JD093iD07p8305; Dessler, A.E., Zhang, Z., Yang, P., Water-vapor climate feedback inferred from climate fluctuations 2003-2008 (2008) Geophys. Res. Lett, 35, pp. L20704. , doi: 10.1029/2008GL035333; Qiang, F., Liou, K.N., Parameterization of the radiative properties of cirrus clouds (1993) Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences, 50 (13), pp. 